President Trump delivered a speech at the Jamestown Settlement Museum in Virginia to commemorate the 400th anniversary of the first representative legislative assembly in the New World. He praised the history and heritage of Virginia and the commitment to American self-government. The President discussed the struggles and sacrifices made by the early settlers and emphasized the importance of hard work, courage, and self-reliance in shaping the American character. He also acknowledged the arrival of the first enslaved Africans in Virginia in 1619 and the long fight for freedom and equality that followed. President Trump called for the defense and preservation of democratic traditions and emphasized the power and sovereignty of the people. He highlighted the accomplishments of America throughout history and expressed confidence in the country's future. The President concluded his speech by declaring that the United States and Virginia are just getting started and that their future is brighter than ever before.